  "prompt": "English Grammar: Which is more Grammatically Correct - \"I wish I was there\" OR \"I wish I were there\"?",
  "response": "In English grammar, the phrase \"I wish I were there\" is considered more grammatically correct, especially in formal writing. This usage is known as the \"subjunctive mood.\"\n\nHere's a detailed explanation:\n\n1. Subjunctive Mood\n- \"Were\" is used in hypothetical or imaginary situations\n- It indicates a condition that is contrary to fact\n- Applies to all persons (I, you, he/she/it)\n\n2. \"I wish I were there\" is correct because:\n- It expresses a wish or desire that is not currently true\n- It follows the traditional grammatical rule for the subjunctive mood\n- Considered more formal and sophisticated\n\n3. \"I wish I was there\" is:\n- Commonly used in casual speech\n- Considered less formal\n- Grammatically acceptable in conversational English\n- Some modern linguists argue this usage is becoming increasingly acceptable\n\n4. Formal vs. Informal Context\n- In academic or professional writing: Use \"were\"\n- In casual conversation: Both \"was\" and \"were\" are generally understood\n\nRecommendation: In formal writing or professional settings, use \"I wish I were there.\"",
